{
  "text": "As discussed in a previous paper on a WOS PBE solver [CITATION_1] , the efficiency of the code can be improved by setting each atom's contribution to the variance equal. To do this, \u2206G was estimated by running a small number of trajectories, N , from each atom (unless otherwise stated, 15 trajectories were used for this step). The desired size of the error \u03c2 could then be estimated by multiplying \u2206G by the desired error fraction. Because the stochastic GB method is a Monte Carlo method, the expected error in \u2206G is inversely proportional to the square root of the number of samples, N , used in its estimate:",
  "citation_candidates": [
